  COMMAND                  CREATED          STATUS          PORTS                    NAMES\n","<container_id> flight-price-predictor   \"python app.py\"          X minutes ago    Up X minutes    0.0.0.0:5000->5000/tcp   flight-predictor-app\n","```\n","\n","If you don't see your `flight-predictor-app` listed, or its status is not `Up`, it indicates that the container is not running, and you would need to start it using the `docker run` command as previously instructed."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"696837ea"},"source":["# Task\n","Prepare Kubernetes Deployment YAML (`deployment.yaml`) and Kubernetes Service YAML (`service.yaml`) to deploy the Flask application to a Kubernetes cluster. The `deployment.yaml` will specify the Docker image for the Flask application, define the container port, and set resource requests and limits. The `service.yaml` will expose the Flask application, enabling access to the deployed model from outside the Kubernetes cluster."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"94ca0d74"},"source":["## Prepare Kubernetes Deployment YAML\n","\n","### Subtask:\n","Create a Kubernetes Deployment YAML file (deployment.yaml) that specifies the Docker image for the Flask application, defines the container port, and sets resource requests and limits. This will manage the application's pods.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"09c00aa1"},"source":["**Reasoning**:\n","To fulfill the subtask, I will create the `deployment.yaml` file using the `%%writefile` magic command, incorporating all the specified Kubernetes Deployment configurations, including the Docker image, container port, and resource requests/limits.\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"796f987b","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772554282206,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":63,"user":{"displayName":"RAKESH DHANORIYA","userId":"02116516191574127798"}},"outputId":"758e9221-40f0-4b77-864d-5d9472776557"},"source":